1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bc4 {White plays in the spirit of the Italian defence.
Indeed, here the pawn stands on c5 rather than on e5. This continuation is a
relatively rare guest in the practical games of the top players.} Nf6 4. d3 {
The usual continuation.} (4. Nc3 {After this move a transposition to lines of
the Scheveningen type can be expected. The bishop already stands on c4 without
influencing much the move orders. Here is one of the main possibilities -} e6
5. O-O Be7 6. d4 cxd4 7. Nxd4 O-O 8. Bb3 Nc6 (8... a6 $5 {transposes to the
Najdorf system}) 9. Be3 Bd7 10. f4 Nxd4 11. Bxd4 Bc6 12. Qe2 b5 $1 {(a typical
queenside counterattack)} 13. Nxb5 Bxb5 14. Qxb5 Nxe4 15. f5 e5 16. Be3 Bg5 17.
Bxg5 Qxg5 18. Qd3 Nf6 19. Qxd6 Qe3+ 20. Kh1 Ne4 21. Rf3 Nf2+ 22. Kg1 Nh3+ 23.
Kh1 $11) (4. Qe2 {By defending the pawn with the queen, White wants
immediately to occupy the center with moves c3-d4 without unnecessarily
spending time on extra pawn moves.} Nc6 $5 (4... e6 5. c3 Be7 6. d4 cxd4 7.
cxd4 d5) 5. c3 Bg4 {(Black creates a pin and does not allow the planned move
d4)} 6. h3 Bxf3 7. Qxf3 g6 {A typical plan In this pawn structure - Black
develops his bishop on the long diagonal and advances his queenside pawns. A
position with mutual chances arises after} (7... e6 {Yet another interesting
plan for a central breakthrough with d6-d5.} 8. d3 Be7 9. O-O O-O 10. Bb3 d5
11. exd5 (11. Bf4 Bd6 12. exd5 Nxd5 13. Bxd6 Qxd6 14. Nd2 Rfd8 15. Ne4 Qe7 $11)
11... Nxd5 12. Nd2 Qc7 13. Ne4 Rad8 14. a4 h6 15. Re1 Rfe8 $11) 8. O-O ({
too time-consuming is} 8. Bb5 Bg7 9. e5 {and Black achieved a great position
with the resourceful manoeuvre} Nd7 $1 10. exd6 Nde5 $1 11. Qd5 Qb6 12. d7+
Nxd7 13. Na3 Rd8 14. Bxc6 bxc6 15. Qe4 Ne5 16. Nc4 Nxc4 17. Qxc4 O-O 18. O-O
Rd5 19. b3 Rfd8 {in Bartel - Laznicka, Germany, 2015}) 8... Bg7 9. Bb3 O-O 10.
d3 b5 11. Be3 Rb8 12. Qe2 Na5 13. Bc2 (13. Nd2 Qc7 14. Rac1 b4 15. f4 Nxb3 16.
axb3 e6 17. Qf3 Nd7 $11) 13... b4 14. Nd2 Qc7 15. Rfc1 bxc3 16. bxc3 Rb2 17.
Qd1 Rc8 $132) (4. e5 {does not bring any special dividends. Black blocks the
bishop with e6 and activates his own on d6. He has a good pawn structure and
no weaknesses.} dxe5 5. Nxe5 e6 6. Qe2 Bd6 7. b3 a6 8. a4 Bd7 9. Bb2 Nc6 10.
Na3 Nxe5 11. Bxe5 Bc6 12. O-O Bxe5 13. Qxe5 Qd4 14. Qxd4 cxd4 15. f3 Ke7 $11)
4... Nc6 {The most natural square for the knight.} 5. c3 {White wants to
improve the pawn structure in the center and for that purpose his bishop can
retreat to b3 and later to c2.} ({A slow development like} 5. h3 g6 6. O-O Bg7
7. Nc3 O-O 8. a3 a6 9. Ba2 {is pretty innocuous.} b5 10. Be3 Bb7 11. Qd2 e6 {
and Black has a free hand in the center and on the queenside -} 12. Ne2 Qc7 13.
Rad1 a5 14. Ng3 Rfd8 15. Bg5 Rd7 $132) 5... g6 {The most popular continuation.}
6. O-O Bg7 {Take note that pinning the knight on this and on the previous move
is a mistake because of 6/7.Qb3 with double attack!} 7. Bb3 {The bishop has
been exposed to a central strike.} O-O 8. Re1 {According to plan - the pawn on
e4 is defended and d3-d4 is in the air.} (8. h3 {may lead to the main line in
slightly different move order. White will be anyway forced to strengthen the
e4-pawn.} e5 {The same pawn structure arises as in the main line.} (8... b5 {
A typical idea for the Sicilian - Black is striving for activity on the
queenside.} 9. d4 Bb7 (9... cxd4 10. cxd4 Bb7 11. Qe2 b4 12. Rd1 a5 $132) 10.
Qe2 Qb6 11. e5 Ne8 12. Be3 cxd4 13. cxd4 Na5 14. Bc2 Nc4 15. Nbd2 Nxe3 16. Qxe3
dxe5 17. dxe5 Qxe3 18. fxe3 Nc7 $15) (8... b6 $5 {deserves attention - here
Black wants to develop the bishop on a6, from where he will target the d3-pawn.
} 9. Re1 Ba6 10. Bc2 Rc8 11. Nbd2 Nd7 12. Nf1 Nde5 13. Bg5 Qd7 14. Nxe5 dxe5
15. Ne3 f6 16. Bh4 e6 $132) 9. Re1 Re8 10. Be3 (10. Bg5 $5 h6 11. Bxf6 Qxf6 12.
Nbd2 Bd7 13. a4 Rac8 14. Nc4 h5 15. Ne3 Bh6 16. Qe2 Be6 $11) 10... b6 11. Nbd2
Bb7 12. d4 (12. Nh2 Qd7 13. Ng4 Na5 14. Ba4 b5 15. Bc2 Nxg4 16. hxg4 a6 $132)
12... exd4 13. cxd4 cxd4 14. Nxd4 Ne5 15. Bg5 h6 16. Bh4 d5 ({Black can still
wait for the most appropriate moment for this break -} 16... a6 17. f3 b5) ({or
} 16... Rc8) 17. f4 Nd3 (17... dxe4 {is objectively simpler, based on} 18. Nxe4
Nc4 $1 19. Bxc4 $140 Rxe4 20. Rxe4 Bxe4 21. Nb5 Qf8 22. Qd6 Rd8 23. Qxf8+ Kxf8
24. Re1 a6 25. Bxf6 Bxf6 26. Rxe4 axb5 27. Bxb5 Bxb2 $11) 18. e5 Nxe1 19. Qxe1
Qb8 20. Ba4 ({it was better to insert} 20. Bxf6 Bxf6 21. Ba4 Re7 22. Qf2 Bg7
23. Nc6 Qc7 24. Nxe7+ Qxe7 25. Nf3 $14) 20... Ne4 21. Nxe4 dxe4 22. Qg3 Qc8 23.
Qe3 Qc4 24. Bxe8 Rxe8 $15 {Bortnyk - Sjugirov, Minsk, 2017.}) 8... e5 $5 {
Black is fighting for the central squares. There are familiar alternatives:} (
8... b5 9. h3 a5 {Black is further expanding on the queenside.} ({Less
ambitious is} 9... Bb7 10. d4 e6 11. dxc5 dxc5 12. Qe2 Qb6 13. Nbd2 Nd7 14. a4
a6 15. Bc2 c4 16. Nf1 Nce5 17. Nxe5 Nxe5 18. Be3 Qc6 19. Bd4 Rfd8 20. axb5 axb5
21. Rxa8 Rxa8 $11) 10. a4 ({the humble} 10. a3 {would reach the game Timofeev
- Sakaev, Sochi, 2005, in which a draw was unexpectedly agreed after} a4 11.
Ba2 Bb7 12. Be3 Qc7 13. Nbd2 e5 $15 14. Rc1 h6 15. Nf1 Na5) 10... b4 11. d4 e6
$1 {A prophylactic and worth remembering measure - now the range of Bb3 is
limited, as well as a probable breakthrough with e5-e6 is out of question.
Regarding the seized space, Black has many active continuations to choose from.
One of them cannot be stopped even by the bizarre Stockfish preference for} 12.
Bg5 h6 13. Bf4 $5 {and now} Ba6 14. dxc5 dxc5 15. Nbd2 ({critical is} 15. Bd6
c4 $5 16. Bxf8 Qxf8 17. e5 $8 Nd5 18. Bc2 Rd8 19. Qe2 Qe7 $44) 15... Nh5 16.
Be3 Qc7 17. Qc1 ({winning a pawn by} 17. Bxc5 $6 bxc3 18. bxc3 {can end even
worse -} Rfd8 19. Be3 Nf4 20. Bxf4 Qxf4 $17) ({the text is avoiding the neat
tactic} 17. Qc2 Rfd8 18. Bc4 Nd4 $1) 17... Nf4 18. Bxf4 Qxf4 19. Bc4 {and
White finally seems close to equality -} Bb7 20. Bb5 Ne5 21. Nxe5 Bxe5 22. g3
Qf6 23. Nc4 Kg7 24. Rb1 Bc7 $11) (8... b6 9. Nbd2 Ba6 10. Nf1 e6 $5 (10... Ne5
{Ruck - Edouard, Skopje, 2019}) 11. h3 Rc8 $132) 9. Nbd2 {This type of
position is usual for Ruy Lopez, including the knight transfer through
d2-f1-g3. But here Black has managed to fianchetto his bishop,. while in the
regular Ruy Lopez he must spend extra time for playing Re8, g6, Be7-f8-g7.} (9.
h3 {White continues to prepare d3-d4 by eliminating the pin from g4.} h6 10. d4
cxd4 11. cxd4 exd4 12. Nxd4 d5 $1 {With this strike in the center Black gets
rid of the isolated pawn on d6.} 13. e5 ({Exchanges in the center do not pose
problems in front of Black.} 13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. Nc3 Nxe4 15. Nxe4 dxe4 16. Bf4
Qh4 17. Bg3 Qg5 18. Rc1 Bf5 19. Rxc6 Rad8 20. Rd6 Rxd6 21. Qxd6 Rd8 22. Qc7 Rd7
23. Qb8+ Qd8 24. Qxd8+ Rxd8 $11 {An equal endgame arises.}) (13. exd5 Nxd5 14.
Nxc6 bxc6 15. Nd2 Re8 16. Nc4 Ba6 17. Rxe8+ Qxe8 18. Bd2 Bxc4 19. Bxc4 Bxb2 20.
Rb1 Bg7 21. Rb7 $44 Rb8 22. Qb3 Rxb7 23. Qxb7 Nb6 24. Bb3 Qd7 25. Qxd7 Nxd7 26.
Ba4 Ne5 27. Be3 a6 $11 28. f4 $140 Nd3 (28... Nc4 29. Bf2 Nb2 30. Bxc6 Nd3 31.
Be3 Nb4 {leads to the same}) 29. Bxc6 Nb4 30. Bb7 Nxa2 31. Bxa6) 13... Ne4 {
with decent counterplay for Black - all his minor pieces are active.} 14. Nf3
Be6 15. Nc3 Re8 $5 16. Nxd5 Na5 17. Nc7 $5 Qxc7 18. Bxe6 Nxf2 19. Qd7 Re7 20.
Qxc7 Rxc7 21. Bxf7+ Rxf7 22. Kxf2 Re8 23. Kg3 Nc6 24. Bf4 g5 25. Bd2 Nxe5 26.
Bc3 Rfe7 27. Nd4 Ng6 28. Nf5 Rxe1 29. Rxe1 Rxe1 30. Bxe1 Bxb2 31. Nxh6+ Kg7 32.
Ng4 $11) 9... h6 {It is useful to take prevents the g5 square under control.}
10. Nf1 d5 $1 {Time has come for activity in the center.} 11. Ng3 Be6 {Black
has arranged his pieces perfectly. He has some good plans - to close the
position in the center with moving his pawn to d4 or exchange it with an
approximate equality.} 12. Bd2 (12. Ba4 Nd7 13. Bd2 d4 14. Bxc6 bxc6 15. Qc1
Kh7 16. cxd4 cxd4 17. Qxc6 Qb8 18. Rec1 Qxb2 19. Rcb1 Rfc8 20. Qa6 Qc2 21. Rc1
Qb2 $11) (12. h3 Re8 {would transpose to McShane - Van Wely, Dordrecht, 2001,
