in a practical game it is extremely difficult to prove such an assessment..}
14. c4 bxc4 15. exf7+ Kxf7 16. Nd2 Bh6 (16... c3 $5 17. Nc4 cxb2 18. Bxb2 Nf4
19. Ne5+ Kg8 20. Qc4+ N6d5 21. Rae1 e6 22. Bc1 Bxe5 23. Rxe5 Qf6 24. Rfe1 $44)
17. Ne4 Bxc1 18. Raxc1 Nxe4 19. Bxe4 e6 20. Qxc4 Qg5+ 21. Kh1 Rhd8 $132 {
Mamedov - Nepomniachtchi, 2019.}) 14. Qxe6 (14. a4 {deserves more attention
here. White is exerting more pressure, probing for new weaknesses on the
queenside.} Kf7 15. Re1 Qb6 16. Nd2 Rhd8 17. Ne4 Kg8 18. Ng5 Nf8 $132) 14...
Nc7 15. Qh3 Nf6 ({Preventing a possible pin along the d-file.} 15... O-O 16.
Rd1 e6 17. Nd2 Ne5 18. Ne4 Nxf3+ 19. Kh1 Qh4 20. Qxh4 Nxh4 21. Bg5 Nf3 22. Be7
Rf7 23. Bxc5 $14) 16. Nd2 Qc8 {Black would be glad to exchange the queens.} (
16... O-O 17. f4 Nh5 18. Ne4 Qc8 19. Qxc8 Raxc8 20. Nxc5 Nxf4 21. Be3 $14) 17.
Qh4 $5 {White is naturally still dreaming of a kingside attack.} ({The endgame
after} 17. Qxc8+ Rxc8 18. Ne4 c4 19. Rd1 O-O 20. a4 Rfd8 21. Rxd8+ Rxd8 22.
axb5 axb5 23. Nxf6+ Bxf6 {is roughly equal.}) 17... O-O {The king is finally
in safety. Black can now press the doubled f-pawns.} 18. Ne4 c4 19. Ng5 (19.
Rd1 Rd8 20. Rxd8+ Qxd8 21. Bf4 Ne6 22. Be3 Qe8 23. f4 Nd5 24. Rd1 Rd8 $132)
19... Ne6 $5 {Getting rid of the most active piece.} 20. Re1 Nxg5 21. Bxg5 Ra7
$11 {White's pair of bishops seem to compensate his wrecked kingside structure.
} *

