1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Nd7 4. O-O {The main continuation, played by many
strong players.} a6 {Questioning the bishop, which cannot retreat to a4.} 5.
Bd3 {The most popular continuation, planning c3, Bc2 and then d4.} ({for} 5.
Bxd7+ Bxd7 6. d4 cxd4 7. Qxd4 Rc8 $132 {see Chapter 7}) (5. Be2 Ngf6 6. d3 $132
{is mentioned there as well}) 5... Ngf6 6. c3 b5 $5 {The most accurate move
order in this system. Black immediately starts his counterplay on the
queenside and prepares the development of his bishop.} 7. a4 {A typical break.}
({The position after} 7. Bc2 $5 Bb7 8. Qe2 g6 $5 (8... e6 9. d4 Be7 10. Nbd2
Qc7 11. Bd3 O-O 12. Re1 Rfe8 13. Nf1 cxd4 14. cxd4 Rac8 15. Ng3 Nb6 16. Bd2 Nc4
17. Rac1 Qb6 18. Bc3 d5 19. e5 Nd7 20. b3 b4 21. Ba1 Na3 22. h4 $14) 9. d4 Bg7
$132 {is examined in the Chapter 2.}) 7... Bb7 $1 {The best move in this
position - Black sacrifices the b5-pawn in return for the central one on e4.} (
7... c4 $2 {This advance appeares to be premature. Black does not have time to
complete the development of his pieces in a comfortable way because of} 8. Be2
$1 Bb7 9. axb5 axb5 10. Rxa8 Bxa8 11. Na3 Bxe4 12. Nxb5 d5 13. b3 (13. Qa4 {
/\b3, Pijpers}) 13... cxb3 14. Qxb3 e6 15. Ba3 (15. d4 $5 $16) 15... Bxf3 (
15... Be7 16. Nfd4 Nc5 17. Qa2 $18) (15... Nc5 $6 16. Qb4 Bxf3 17. gxf3 Be7 18.
Rb1 Ncd7 19. Nd6+ Kf8 20. Qa4 {/\21.Rb7+- Svidler - Nepomniachtchi, 2018}) 16.
Bxf3 Be7 17. Nd6+ Kf8 {and Black's position looks solid, but under perminent
piece pressure after} 18. c4 (18. Re1 $5) 18... dxc4 19. Qxc4 g6 20. Rb1 Kg7
21. Nb7 Qf8 22. Bb2) (7... b4 $5 {is an interesting opportunity, Black.does
not force the events.} 8. Bc2 Bb7 9. Re1 Qc7 {Black has a concrete strong idea
against} 10. d4 (10. d3 a5 $5 {Yet untried, but quite logical reaction.} ({
In the known games} 10... e6 11. a5 bxc3 12. bxc3 Be7 13. h3 O-O 14. Bf4 Bc6
15. Nbd2 Bb5 {McShane - Nepomniachtchi, Batumi, 2018,} 16. Qe2 $14) ({and} 
10... g6 11. Nbd2 bxc3 12. bxc3 Bg7 13. d4 O-O 14. Bd3 cxd4 15. cxd4 e5 16. Ba3
$1 {Tomashevsky - Dominguez Perez, blitz, 2016, Black allowed 11.a5, but there
is no reason to do so}) 11. Nbd2 (11. d4 e5) 11... e6 12. Nc4 d5 13. exd5 Bxd5
14. Bg5 Be7 15. Bh4 O-O $132) 10... cxd4 11. cxd4 Rc8 12. Bd3 Nxe4 $1 13. Qe2
d5 14. Bxa6 (14. Nbd2 $5 e6 15. Nb3 Nb8 16. Ne5 Bd6 17. Be3 O-O $132) 14...
Bxa6 15. Qxa6 e6 (15... Qxc1 $2 16. Nc3 $18) 16. Be3 (16. Nbd2 Nd6 17. Nf1 Nb8
18. Qd3 Be7 19. Bf4 Qc4 20. Qd2 Qa6 21. Ne5 O-O $11) 16... Bd6 17. Nbd2 O-O {
While the opponent was busy to win the pawn back, Black completed his
development without any trouble. Here is a curious sample line with a likely
draw in the end -} 18. Nxe4 dxe4 19. Rec1 Qb8 20. Rxc8 Rxc8 21. Nd2 Bxh2+ 22.
Kh1 Rc2 23. g3 Bxg3 24. fxg3 Qxg3 25. Qa8+ Nf8 26. Qxe4 Rxb2 27. Qf3 Qxf3+ 28.
Nxf3 Rb3 29. Re1 Ra3 30. Ne5 Rxa4 31. Rb1 $11) 8. axb5 {White accepts the
challenge.} (8. Re1 e6 ({for} 8... c4 9. Bc2 e6 {see more in Chapter 4 (the
