{1024MB, Rybka3Gen.ctg} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Nd7 4. O-O a6 5. Bd3 Ngf6 6.
Re1 $5 {One of the most popular plans. White is going to retreat the bighop to
f1 and then play the desired c3-d4.} (6. c3 b5 7. Re1 (7. Bc2 Bb7 8. Qe2 g6 $5
9. d4 Bg7 $132 {is examined in Chapter 2}) 7... Bb7 (7... e6 $5 {transposes to
the rapid game Najer - Cheparinov, Dubai, 2014, in which the move order has
been 6.Re1 e6 7.c3 b5!? with} 8. Bc2 c4 {next}) 8. Bc2 c4 $5 {A typical idea
in this structure with a bishop on c2. Black establishes the queenside and
nearly all the pawn exchanges are welcome for him.} 9. a4 (9. d4 {reaches a
fine version of Open Sicilian after} cxd3 10. Qxd3 (10. Bxd3 e6 11. Bg5 Be7 12.
Nbd2 h6 13. Bh4 O-O) 10... e6 {with yet another transposition to Najer -
Cheparinov, while going for the central pawn with} (10... Nc5 11. Qe2 Bxe4 12.
Bxe4 Ncxe4 {is met by} 13. a4 bxa4 14. Rxa4 {and most probably Black's best is
to return the pawn -} d5 15. Rxa6 Rxa6 16. Qb5+ $5 Nd7 $1 17. Qxa6 e6 {with
approximate equality})) ({his prospects are better in case of} 9. b3 e6 10.
bxc4 bxc4 11. Na3 Rc8 12. Rb1 Ba8 13. Qe2 d5 14. Nd4 Nxe4 15. Bxe4 dxe4 16.
Nxc4 Be7 $15 {as well}) 9... e6 10. axb5 ({Later MVL switched to} 10. d4 cxd3
11. Qxd3 Nc5 12. Qe2 bxa4 13. e5 dxe5 14. Nxe5 Bd6 (14... Be7 15. Rd1 Qc8 16.
Rxa4 $1 Nxa4 17. Bxa4+ Kf8 18. Na3 $5 Bxa3 19. bxa3 {and here Giri committed 
(a capture on c3 could have justified the brave decision on the previous move)
a grave mistake -} Ke7 $2 20. Qb2 a5 {, probably missing in the nick of time}
21. Be3 $1 {with irresistable threats, Vachier-Lagrave - Giri, Stavanger,
blitz, 2017}) 15. Nd2 (15. Bg5 h6 16. Bh4 Bxe5 17. Qxe5 Qd5 18. Qxd5 Nxd5 19.
Bxa4+ Nxa4 20. Rxa4 {, about equal, Tari - Najer, Turkey, 2017}) 15... Bxe5 ({
Black will anyway be practically forced to this exchange after} 15... Nfd7 16.
Bxa4 $1) 16. Qxe5 Nd3 17. Bxd3 Qxd3 18. Rxa4 O-O 19. Rb4 (19. Rd4 Qb5 20. Qg3
Rfd8 21. Rb4 Qc6 22. Nf3 a5 23. Rh4 Qd6 $1 $11 24. Bf4 $140 (24. Ne5 $6 {
runs into} Ne4 25. Qf4 f6) 24... Qd3 25. Bc7 Rd7 26. Be5 Qg6 (26... Ne8 {
is a plausible alternative})) 19... Qd5 20. f3 a5 $1 (20... Qxe5 $6 21. Rxe5
$14) 21. Rd4 Qxe5 22. Rxe5 Nd5 23. Ne4 a4 (23... h6 24. Nd6 Bc6 25. c4 Rfd8 26.
Nxf7 Kxf7 27. cxd5 Rxd5 28. Rexd5 Bxd5 29. Ra4 Bb3 30. Rf4+ Kg6 31. Bd2 a4 32.
Bc3 h5 33. Rb4 Bd5 $11) 24. Nd6 Rfb8 25. c4 Ne7 26. Rd3 Bc6 $11) 10... axb5 11.
Rxa8 Qxa8 12. Na3 Bxe4 (12... Be7 13. Nxb5 O-O 14. Qe2 Rc8 {was introduced in
practice by Topalov in 2016. The extra pawn is of little use, White should be
instead concerned about the prospects of his dark-squared bishop, for example}
15. Nbd4 (15. Na3 {was tried twice by Vachier-Lagrave in the predecessors with
Topalov and the Frenchman had to be happy to draw both of them}) (15. d3 cxd3
16. Bxd3 Nc5 17. Nd2 Nxd3 18. Qxd3 Ba6 19. c4 {and here a draw was agreed in D.
Stojanovic - M. Yilmaz, Serbia, team, 2018, though Black could continue -} d5
20. exd5 Bxb5 21. cxb5 Qxd5 22. Qxd5 Nxd5 {with a risk-free small, but lasting
endgame advantage}) 15... g6 16. b4 cxb3 17. Nxb3 Qa2 18. Qd1 e5 $44 {and
White's queenside is still leaving a sad impression, Liang - Yilmaz, Rejkjavik,
