7... g6 8. Re1 Bg7 9. d4 ({unnecessary is} 9. h3 O-O 10. d4 cxd4 11. cxd4 d5
12. e5 Ne4 13. Nbd2 Nxd2 14. Bxd2 Rfc8 15. Rc1 Nd8 16. Qb3 Rc6 17. Rxc6 Nxc6
18. h4 Rc8 19. g3 e6 20. Rc1 h5 $11) (9. Bf4 O-O 10. Nbd2 b5 11. h3 Nh5 12. Bh2
Rab8 13. Rc1 e5 14. a4 b4 $11) 9... e6 $5 10. d5 (10. dxc5 dxc5 {already
resembles the main line in Chapter 1}) 10... exd5 11. exd5+ Ne7 12. c4 O-O 13.
Nc3 a6 14. a4 Rae8 15. Qd3 {and, if nothing more from White's point of view,
the present position is a better version of the final one in this chapter}) 8.
Bf4 Be7 9. Nbd2 O-O 10. Re1 b5 11. h3 Qb7 12. a4 a6 13. e5 dxe5 14. Nxe5 Nxe5
15. Bxe5 Rfd8 16. Qe2 b4 $15) 4... g6 {The most common reaction in this
structure - the bishop will show greatest efficacy on the long diagonal.} (4...
Nxe4 $4 5. Qa4+ Nc6 6. Qxe4 $18) 5. O-O Bg7 6. Bb5+ $5 {The best continuation
- after the exchange of the bishops White will defend the e4-pawn with Re1 and
push the other central one to d4.} (6. Re1 {White wants to rearrange the
pieces by playing Bf1 and then the planned move d4.} O-O 7. Bf1 Nc6 8. h3 (8.
d4 cxd4 9. cxd4 Bg4 {Here Black manages to create an unpleasant pin with every
chance to take over the initiative.} 10. d5 Ne5 11. Nbd2 Qa5 12. Be2 Nxf3+ 13.
Bxf3 Bxf3 14. Nxf3 Rac8 15. Bd2 Qb6 16. Bc3 Ng4 17. Qd2 Bxc3 18. bxc3 Rc5 19.
Rab1 Qc7 $15) (8. d3 h6 9. a3 e5 10. b4 Be6 11. Nbd2 b5 ({the patient} 11... a6
$15 {would have been better}) 12. Bb2 ({missing the best moment for opening
the center -} 12. d4 $1 exd4 13. Bxb5 dxc3 14. Bxc6 Rc8 15. b5 cxd2 16. Bxd2
Nd7 17. Rc1 {and here the precise} Bg4 $1 {with the practically forced sequence
} 18. Bf4 Ne5 19. Bxe5 Bxe5 20. h3 Bxf3 21. Qxf3 {leads to a balanced position}
) 12... Qb6 13. Rb1 a6 14. Ba1 {(this regrouping disabled the ideas with a6-a5,
so Black's attention normally shifted to the center)} Rfe8 15. h3 cxb4 16. axb4
d5 $15 {Becerra Rivero - Najer, Philadelphia 2008}) 8... e5 $1 {A very strong
move! The pin from g4 is no longer an option and Black is fighting differently
for the central squares by threatening a direct breakthrough with d6-d5.} 9. d4
$6 ({as we are going to see, the open confrontation is not a fun for White,
similar is with the slow development with} 9. d3 {, which does not promise him
much either -} d5 10. Nbd2 Re8 11. a3 d4 12. cxd4 cxd4 13. b4 b6 14. Rb1 Bb7
$15) 9... cxd4 10. cxd4 exd4 11. Nxd4 Nxd4 12. Qxd4 Re8 $1 {The point of the
whole idea behind 8...e5! White's center is in danger of being utterly
destroyed:} {White will be once again a pawn down in an ending with
opposite-coloured bishops after} 13. Bb5 ({not recommendable is} 13. Bg5 $6 h6
$1 14. Bxf6 Qxf6 ({or} 14... Bxf6 15. Qd2 d5 $1) 15. Qxf6 Bxf6 16. Nc3 Be6 $15)
({natural is} 13. Qd3 {, though Black has then no less than 3(!) ways to
finish with the e4-pawn:} Bf5 ({apart from the most frequently played 13...d5,
Black has the direct} 13... Rxe4 14. Rxe4 Bf5 15. f3 (15. Nc3 $142 Nxe4 ({
it is notable that the immediate} 15... d5 $6 16. Bg5 $1 {offers new
opportunities, for instance} dxe4 $2 17. Qxd8+ Rxd8 18. g4 $1 {is advantageous
for White!}) 16. Nxe4 d5 {transposes to the leading line with 13...Bf5}) 15...
d5 {, based on} 16. g4 Qc7 $1 17. Bf4 dxe4 18. Bxc7 exd3 19. gxf5 Nd5 20. Nc3
Nxc7 $15 {/-/+}) 14. Nc3 (14. Bg5 Rxe4 15. Rxe4 Bxe4 16. Qd2 Bxb1 17. Bxf6 Bxf6
18. Rxb1 d5 19. Rd1 d4 $15) (14. f3 $6 d5 15. g4 $140 Qc7 $1) 14... Nxe4 $1 {
(a beautiful tactical point!)} 15. Nxe4 (15. g4 Nxc3 16. Rxe8+ Qxe8 17. gxf5
Na4 18. fxg6 hxg6 $17) 15... Rxe4 16. Rxe4 d5 17. Bg5 $1 (17. Qb5 Bxe4 18. Qxb7
Qc8 $17 {- White's queenside is in terrible shape}) 17... Bxe4 18. Bxd8 Bxd3
19. Bxd3 Rxd8 20. Rc1 {with chances to survive}) 13... Re5 $1 ({the most
popular is} 13... Bd7 14. Bxd7 Qxd7 15. Qd3 Qc6 (15... Rad8 16. Nc3 d5 17. Bg5
dxe4 18. Qxd7 Rxd7 19. Bxf6 Bxf6 20. Nxe4 Kg7 21. Nxf6 Rxe1+ 22. Rxe1 Kxf6 23.
Re2 $11) 16. Nc3 d5 {, but White is not worse after} 17. e5 Ne4 18. Nxd5 Rxe5
19. Rd1 Nc5 20. Qf3 Rae8 21. Bf4 $1 (21. Be3 $2 Rf5 $1) 21... Re4 {and only now
} 22. Be3 $1 (22. Nc3 $6 Bxc3 23. bxc3 Qf6 24. Be3 Qxf3 25. gxf3 Rc4 {and,
after being saddled with so many islands, White eventually lost, Rainfray -
Degraeve, France, tt, 2001}) 22... Bxb2 23. Rab1 Bg7 24. Bxc5 Qxc5 25. Rxb7 f5)
14. Nc3 ({Black's chances are higher in the tense line} 14. Bc4 Bf5 15. Nc3
Nxe4 16. Bxf7+ Kxf7 17. Nxe4 Kf8 18. Bg5 Rxe4 19. Qxe4 Qxg5 20. Qxb7 Rc8) 14...
Nxe4 $1 15. Nxe4 Rxb5 16. Qxd6 Bf5 17. Qxd8+ Rxd8 18. Nd6 $5 Bxb2 19. Nxb5 Bxa1
20. Bg5 Rd5 21. Nc7 Rc5 22. Rxa1 Rxc7 23. Rc1 Rd7 $15) 6... Bd7 {It is much
more logical to exchange a piece, which is about to make 3 out of the first 7
moves, compared to} (6... Nbd7 7. Re1 O-O 8. d4 a6 9. Bf1 {and Black has to
look for a playable position of Italian/Ruy Lopez type after} e5 ({rather than
} 9... cxd4 10. cxd4 b5 11. a3 Bb7 {when White has the comfort to play} 12. Nc3
$14)) 7. Bxd7+ Nbxd7 8. Re1 {White has defended the e-pawn and is ready to
play d4 in one go.} O-O 9. d4 Rc8 $1 {A very subtle move. Black's rook is
ready to make use of the c-file after exchanging on d4.} 10. h3 {Denying the
knight access to g4 in reply to 11.e5, but it has another good retreat. In
this sense the text might be a waste of time, White has various alternatives:}
(10. Nbd2 cxd4 11. cxd4 e5 12. Nb3 (12. d5 Nc5 13. Qe2 Qa5 14. b3 b5 15. Bb2
Bh6 $15) 12... exd4 13. Qxd4 Nb6 14. Bg5 h6 15. Bxf6 Bxf6 16. Qd2 Nc4 17. Qxh6
Bg7 18. Qh3 Nxb2 $15) (10. Bg5 Qb6 11. Qe2 e6 12. Na3 cxd4 13. Nxd4 d5 14. exd5
Nxd5 15. Rad1 h6 16. Bh4 N7f6 $11) (10. Qe2 e6 11. Bf4 Qc7 12. Na3 a6 13. Rad1
cxd4 14. cxd4 b5 $132) (10. a4 e6 11. Bg5 Qb6 12. e5 Nd5 13. c4 $1 Qxb2 14. Ra3
N5b6 15. Rb3 Qa1 16. Ra3 Qb2 $11) (10. Bf4 Qb6 11. Qe2 cxd4 12. cxd4 d5 13. e5
Ne4 14. Nbd2 f5 15. Nb3 e6 16. Rec1 a5 17. Rxc8 Rxc8 18. Nc1 Bf8 19. Nd3 Be7
20. h4 Rc4 21. b3 Rc6 22. Rc1 Nb8 23. Qb2 Qa6 24. Rxc6 Nxc6 25. Qc2 b5 26. g3
$11) (10. a3 Qc7 11. Bg5 cxd4 12. cxd4 Qc2 13. Nbd2 h6 $1 14. Be3 Ng4 $15) ({
Rc8 will not remain passive for long after} 10. d5 $5 c4 $1 11. Qe2 Nc5 12. Na3
Re8 13. Nxc4 Ncxe4 14. Rd1 Qd7 15. Ne3 Nc5 16. h3 b5 $15) ({premature is} 10.
e5 dxe5 11. dxe5 Ng4 12. e6 Nde5 13. exf7+ Rxf7 14. Ng5 Qxd1 15. Rxd1 Rff8 16.
f3 Rfd8 17. Rd2 {A very characteristic move for this variation - the march
e5-e6 caused damage to Black's pawn formation, but at high price. The
undeveloped queenside leaves a sad impression and, apart from somply
retreating the knight, there is a tricky opportunity like} Bh6 $5 18. fxg4 Nd3
$1 {(a neat tactical point!)} 19. Na3 Nxc1 20. Rxd8+ Rxd8 21. Rxc1 Bxg5 22. Rc2
a6 23. Nc4 b5 24. Ne5 Bf4 25. Nf3 c4 $15) 10... Qb6 $1 {An essential move -
the queen is located perfectly on this square! The opponent is prepared to meet
} (10... d5 11. e5 Ne4 12. Nbd2 f5 13. exf6 Ndxf6 14. Nxe4 Nxe4 15. dxc5 Nxc5
16. Be3 Qd6 {and here, instead of} 17. Nd4 $6 a6 18. Nb3 b6 (18... Na4 $5) 19.
Qe2 e5 $11 {, Theodorou - Heimann, Novi Sad 2016, White could preserve some
advantage due to his better pawn structure by exchanging his bishop for the
knight or with 17.Bd4.}) 11. d5 {White closes the center.} (11. Qe2 {may well
be tetter than the text - White is overprotecting his b-pawn, but bringing the
bishop into play will not mean a solution of all the trouble with it.} e6 $1
12. Bf4 (12. Nbd2 cxd4 13. cxd4 Rc6 14. b3 Rfc8 15. Bb2 Rc2 16. Rac1 Qa5 17. a4
Rxc1 18. Bxc1 Qb4 $15) 12... cxd4 13. cxd4 d5 14. e5 Ne4 15. Nbd2 $5 {(after
the change in the central structure Nd7 is temporarily misplaced and the text
is a clever attempt to profit at once from it)} Rc2 16. Qd3 Qxb2 (16... Rxb2
17. Nxe4 dxe4 18. Qxe4 Qc6 (18... Qa6 19. Bc1 Rxa2 20. Rxa2 Qxa2 21. Qxb7 Nb6
22. Bd2 Nd5 23. Rc1 $1 $132) 19. Qxc6 bxc6 20. Reb1 Rfb8 21. Rc1 Rc8 22. Rcb1
Rcb8 23. Rc1 $11) 17. Rab1 (17. Reb1 Qc3 18. Qb5 Nxe5 19. dxe5 Nxd2 20. Bxd2
Rxd2 21. Nxd2 Qxd2 $44 22. Re1 $140 Rc8 23. Rad1 Qxa2 24. Qxb7 Qc2 25. Qxa7
Bxe5) 17... Qxa2 18. Ra1 Qb2 19. Rxa7 Nc3 20. Rxb7 Qxb7 21. Qxc2 Rc8 22. Nf1 {
, about equal, but Black is the active side on the queenside}) (11. e5 Nd5 $1 {
Here Black has a good d5-square for the knight.} 12. dxc5 (12. c4 {is
effectively met by} Nc7 $1 {and White's center begins to collapse.} 13. exd6
Qxd6 14. d5 b5 15. Bg5 Nf6 $1 ({it takes quite an effort from White to keep
the balance after} 15... Rfe8 16. Nbd2 bxc4 17. Nxc4 Qxd5 18. Rxe7 Rxe7 19.
Bxe7 Nb6 20. Nd6 Rb8 21. Qc2 Qc6 22. Re1 Ne6 23. Qe4 $1 Qxe4 $140 24. Nxe4 Bxb2
25. Nxc5 Nd5 26. Nxe6 Nxe7 27. Nf4) {the lesser evil is} 16. Nc3 (16. Na3 bxc4
17. Nxc4 Qxd5 {leaves White in a desperate search for a compensation for the
missing pawn:} 18. Nce5 (18. Qxd5 Ncxd5 19. Rad1 e6) (18. Nfe5 Rfd8 19. Qxd5 (
19. Qa4 Ne6 20. Rad1 Qb7) 19... Ncxd5 20. Rac1 Ne8 (20... Nb6 21. Nf3 h6 22.
Bd2 Nxc4 23. Rxc4 Nd5) 21. Bd2 f6) (18. Qa4 Ne6 19. Rad1 Nd4) 18... Rfd8 (18...
Ne6 19. Bxf6 Qxd1 20. Raxd1 Bxf6 21. Nd7 Rfd8 22. Nxf6+ exf6) 19. Qa4 Ne6 20.
Qxa7 Ne4 21. Bxe7 Bxe5 22. Nxe5 Qxe5 23. Bxd8 Rxd8) 16... bxc4 17. Ne5 Nfxd5
18. Nxc4 Qc6 19. Nxd5 Nxd5 20. Bxe7 Rfe8 21. Bg5 Rxe1+ 22. Qxe1 Nb6 $1 {
, though the danger for the queenside pawns has not gone}) 12... Qxc5 13. exd6
Qxd6 14. Na3 Qc6 15. Bg5 Rfe8 16. c4 Nc7 17. Nb5 $5 Nxb5 18. cxb5 Qxb5 19. a4
Qc6 20. Rc1 Qd6 21. Rxc8 Rxc8 22. Bxe7 Qxd1 23. Rxd1 Nf8 $11) (11. Nbd2 cxd4 {
(a timely exchange under the best possible conditions, as the knight is
already on d2 instead of the perfect location on c3)} 12. cxd4 e5 13. dxe5 dxe5
14. Nb3 Qe6 15. Bd2 b6 $11) 11... e6 {A typical Benoni central break - Black
is trying to open the position for his better mobilized forces.} 12. c4 {
Now the c3-square is available for the knight, while keeping the center as
solid as possible.} (12. dxe6 fxe6 13. Qb3 d5 14. exd5 exd5 15. Bg5 Rfe8 16.
Nbd2 Qc6 $11) 12... exd5 13. exd5 ({White is too behind in development for
playing} 13. cxd5 $6 Rfe8 14. Nc3 Qa6 $1 15. Bf4 c4 {(this can be played on
any of the previous two moves as well)} 16. Bh2 b5 $15) 13... Rfe8 {Bringing
the last piece into play.} 14. Rxe8+ Rxe8 15. Nc3 Qb4 16. Qf1 Ne4 {Following
the same strategy.} (16... Nb6 $5 17. Nd2 Qa5 18. Nb3 Qb4 19. Nd2 $11) {
To his luck, White has the intermediate} 17. a3 $1 Qb6 18. Nxe4 Rxe4 {Black is
at least equal here.} *

